= Organizational Depth and Abstraction

#import "../lib/template.typ": aside, principle

The DAO is a lens. Look downward and you see hierarchy --- departments, task forces, working groups, each with their own budgets and charters. Look upward and you see federation --- alliances, coalitions, trade networks, where DAOs are the members rather than players.

Both directions use the same primitive. A Sub-DAO is a full DAO. A federation is governed by DAOs. The building block does not change; only the scale and the relationships do.

== Depth

Growth creates internal structure. A tribe that starts as a single DAO eventually needs departments. Engineering, logistics, diplomacy --- each with their own governance, their own vaults, their own charter.

A Sub-DAO is not a permission scope or a lightweight proxy. It is a complete organization in its own right, operating with genuine autonomy within the boundaries set by its parent. It governs itself, manages its own resources, and amends its own charter.

The parent retains oversight. It can replace a compromised board, pause operations, reclaim delegated capabilities, or grant full independence. These controls exist for the same reason a board of directors can override a department head --- accountability flows upward even when authority flows down.

A department that outgrows its parent can be spun out into a sovereign DAO. The control relationship is destroyed permanently. The former department is now a peer, free to form its own relationships. The protocol does not mandate this path --- it provides the mechanism.

== Abstraction

Organizations also compose upward. Peer DAOs may voluntarily form federations --- associations that pool resources and coordinate policy without surrendering sovereignty. Unlike the parent-child relationship, federation membership is symmetric. No member controls another. Any member can exit through their own governance.

Federations can maintain collective treasuries, conduct multi-layer voting, and coordinate policy across member organizations. A department must be spun out to independence before it can join a federation --- federation is a right of sovereign entities.

== The Civilization Mesh

A single DAO can simultaneously be a department of a tribe, a member of a cross-tribe alliance, and the controller of its own sub-departments. These relationships compose without interference. The result is not a tree but a mesh --- a web of organizational relationships at every scale.

#principle[The Mesh][
  Downward is control. Upward is membership. Sideways is alliance. The DAO sits at the intersection of all three, and the mesh emerges from organizations exercising these relationships independently.
]

Within this mesh, a _tempo gradient_ emerges naturally.

At the edges --- small teams, operational Sub-DAOs --- decisions are frequent and fast. A frontier outpost votes daily on resource allocation. Its governance parameters reflect this: low quorum, short voting windows, minimal delays.

Higher up --- tribes, alliances --- decisions are slower and more consequential. A tribal charter amendment takes weeks. A federation trade policy takes longer. The governance parameters reflect the weight of the decision.

Revenue cycles follow the same gradient. Resources flow upward from operational units that generate value daily, through departments that allocate weekly, to parent organizations that budget across seasons. The tempo of money matches the tempo of decisions.

This gradient is not designed. It is not configured centrally. It emerges from each DAO setting its own governance parameters to match its role, its size, and its rhythm. The protocol provides the primitives --- DAOs, vaults, proposals, charters. The civilization mesh, with all its texture and tempo, comes to be from these few simple building blocks and the guarantees they carry.

== Infrastructure as Commons

DAOs can hold infrastructure capabilities in their vaults --- gate controllers, mining rigs, storage networks. This transforms individually owned assets into collectively governed infrastructure.

A gate network becomes a public utility operated by a DAO. A mining fleet becomes a cooperative's shared resource. The organization does not replace the infrastructure. It provides the governance layer that makes collective ownership viable and ensures that infrastructure serves the organization rather than any individual.
